        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"387244\">Yaël Dillies</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/.22graph.22.20of.20a.20relation/near/517067540\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>You might be interested in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/23181\">#23181</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"387244\">@Yaël Dillies</span> I was wondering if there was a more natural way of writing hypothesis <code>hD</code> in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/master/Mathlib/Order/ScottContinuity.lean#L55\">https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/master/Mathlib/Order/ScottContinuity.lean#L55</a><br>\nsomething like:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hD</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">graph</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">·</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">·</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊆</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">D</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Except that doesn't make sense even in traditional maths, as <code>graph (· ≤ ·)</code> is of type <code>Set (α × α)</code> rather than <code>Set (Set α)</code>.</p>",
